Correlation Matrix helps in identifying features that are highly correlated with the target variable or with each other. Highly correlated features may provide redundant or duplicate information, and including them in the feature set may not significantly improve the models performance. In such cases, it is common to select a subset of features that are less correlated with each other and have a stronger correlation with the target variable. Correlational analysis assists in making informed decisions about feature selection and can improve the models interpretability and generalization capabilities.

f. Data Balancing Tasks

Some popular techniques include oversampling (e.g., SMOTE, ADASYN), undersampling (e.g., random undersampling, cluster centroid), and hybrid methods (e.g., SMOTE + Tomek links). These techniques aim to address class imbalance by either increasing the minority class samples or decreasing the majority class samples.The effect of data balancing on model evaluation parameters depends on the specific task, dataset, and imbalance severity. Balancing techniques can improve the performance of models by reducing bias towards the majority class and improving the models ability to correctly classify the minority class. It may lead to better precision, recall, F1-score, and overall accuracy for the minority class. However, its important to carefully evaluate the impact on the evaluation metrics for both classes and consider the trade-offs, as oversampling can lead to overfitting and undersampling can discard potentially valuable information.

It is recommended to experiment with different data balancing techniques and evaluate the performance of the model using appropriate evaluation metrics to determine the most suitable approach for a given problem.</i>

g. Justification for the use of Standardization instead of Normalization

In the provided code, we have chosen to apply Standardization using StandardScaler() from scikit-learn. By standardizing the features, we transform them to have zero mean and unit variance.We justify the choice of feature transformation techniques based on the datasets structure and complexity. Standardization is suitable when the features have different scales and we want to give them equal importance. Normalization (MinMax Scaling) is useful when we want to scale the features to a specific range (e.g., [0, 1]).

In [39]:
# Iterate over the folds
for train_index, val_index in kf.split(X_train1_scaled):
    x_train_fold, x_val_fold = X_train1_scaled[train_index], X_train1_scaled[val_index]
    y_train_fold, y_val_fold = y_train1.iloc[train_index], y_train1.iloc[val_index]
    
    # Perform model training
    model.fit(x_train_fold, y_train_fold)
    
    # Perform model evaluation on training set
    train_score = model.score(x_train_fold, y_train_fold)
    train_scores.append(train_score)
    
    # Perform model evaluation on validation set
    val_score = model.score(x_val_fold, y_val_fold)
    val_scores.append(val_score)
    
    # Print the evaluation results for each fold
    print("Train Score: {:.4f} - Validation Score: {:.4f}".format(train_score, val_score))

Step 4: Explore the need of regularization and incorporate few relevant techniques for the problem statement.

Regularization techniques help prevent overfitting and improve the generalization of the model. L1 regularization promotes sparsity in the model by enforcing some of the coefficients to be exactly zero, while L2 regularization encourages small non-zero coefficients. The impact of L1 and L2 regularization can be observed by comparing the performance of the models with L1 and L2 regularization in terms of accuracy.
